# Financial Performance Benchmarks

Stage-specific and agency-type-specific benchmarks for financial health metrics.

## Universal AGI Margin Rules of Thumb

These ratios apply across all agency types and stages as foundational targets:

| Component | Target Range | Meaning |
|-----------|--------------|---------|
| **Payroll (Labor)** | ≤ 45% of AGI | Labor cost control |
| **Overhead (SG&A)** | ≤ 20% of AGI | Infrastructure efficiency |
| **Operating Profit** | ≥ 35% of AGI | Reinvestment capacity and enterprise value |

### Total Cost Structure Target
**Total Costs (Payroll + SG&A):** ≤ 65% of AGI

## AGI % by Agency Type

The percentage of total revenue that becomes Agency Gross Income (after pass-throughs) varies significantly by business model:

| Agency Type | AGI as % of Revenue | Typical Pass-Through Costs | Value Creation Source |
|-------------|---------------------|---------------------------|----------------------|
| **Media Buying / Performance** | 25-40% | High (ad spend, media placements) | Strategy, optimization, reporting |
| **Creative / Branding / Web** | 60-75% | Moderate (some production, freelancers) | Internal creative capacity |
| **PR / Communications** | 65-80% | Low (mostly internal team) | Relationships, narrative, execution |
| **Strategic / Advisory / Consulting** | 85-95% | Very low (minimal external costs) | Intellectual capital, strategy |

### AGI Quality Implications

**For operators:**
- Higher AGI% = more value captured internally
- Track Net AGI (AGI minus contractor costs) for cleanest efficiency view

**For investors/acquirers:**
- Normalize all agencies to AGI for fair comparison
- High pass-through agencies valued on AGI multiples, not revenue multiples

## Financial Benchmarks by Stage

### Rising Stage (≤$1.5M AGI)

| Metric | Target Range | Focus |
|--------|--------------|-------|
| **AGI %** | 70-85% | Establish value capture patterns |
| **Unburdened Compensation %** | 45-55% | Learning to balance team costs |
| **SG&A %** | 20-30% | Building infrastructure |
| **Operating Profit %** | 10-25% | Survival to stability |
| **Cash Reserves** | 1-2 months | Emergency buffer only |

**Key Challenge:** Achieving consistent profitability month-over-month

---

### Striving Stage ($1.5M-3M AGI)

| Metric | Target Range | Focus |
|--------|--------------|-------|
| **AGI %** | 80-90% | Refining value capture |
| **Unburdened Compensation %** | 40-50% | Efficiency discipline |
| **SG&A %** | 18-25% | Infrastructure maturing |
| **Operating Profit %** | 20-30% | Margin control |
| **Cash Reserves** | 3 months | Reinvestment buffer |

**Key Challenge:** Maintaining margins while scaling team

---

### Thriving Stage ($3M-7M AGI)

| Metric | Target Range | Focus |
|--------|--------------|-------|
| **AGI %** | 85-92% | High value capture |
| **Unburdened Compensation %** | 38-45% | Optimized efficiency |
| **SG&A %** | 15-22% | Mature infrastructure |
| **Operating Profit %** | 30-35% | Strong profitability |
| **Cash Reserves** | 4-6 months | Strategic flexibility |

**Key Challenge:** Scaling systems without margin compression

---

### Driving Stage ($7M-15M+ AGI)

| Metric | Target Range | Focus |
|--------|--------------|-------|
| **AGI %** | 90-95% | Exceptional value capture |
| **Unburdened Compensation %** | 35-42% | Elite efficiency |
| **SG&A %** | 15-20% | Optimized infrastructure |
| **Operating Profit %** | 35-45% | Enterprise-grade margins |
| **Cash Reserves** | 6-12 months | Capitalization and optionality |

**Key Challenge:** Maintaining margins at scale while building enterprise value

## Cost Ratio Dynamics

### The See-Saw Effect

When AGI% improves (less pass-through, more retained value):
- Compensation% and SG&A% naturally decline *as percentages* even if absolute costs stay flat
- Profit% amplifies geometrically with each efficiency gain

### Compounding Improvements

**Example:**
- 5% improvement in AGI% can ripple into +8-10% profit improvement
- Because it amplifies both productivity and overhead efficiency simultaneously

### Decline Compounds Faster

When AGI% falls (more outsourcing, pricing concessions):
- Every cost ratio instantly worsens
- Creates profit compression spiral unless corrected quickly

## Warning Thresholds

### Yellow Flags (Monitor Closely)

| Metric | Threshold | Indication |
|--------|-----------|------------|
| **Compensation %** | 45-50% | Efficiency slipping; review roles/pricing |
| **SG&A %** | 20-25% | Overhead creeping; audit spend |
| **Operating Profit %** | 25-30% | Margin pressure; identify levers |

### Red Flags (Immediate Action)

| Metric | Threshold | Indication |
|--------|-----------|------------|
| **Compensation %** | > 50% | Severe inefficiency or under-pricing |
| **SG&A %** | > 25% | Overhead bloat; structural issue |
| **Operating Profit %** | < 20% | Unsustainable; margin crisis |
| **Total Costs %** | > 70% | Business model under stress |

## Consistency as a KPI

### Why Stability Matters

Agencies showing stable ratios within target ranges exhibit:
- **Predictable earnings** → investor confidence
- **Scalable growth runway** → hiring confidence  
- **Systemic maturity** → valuation premium

### Variance Monitoring

Track quarter-over-quarter variance:
- **Healthy variance:** ≤5% movement in cost ratios
- **Attention needed:** 5-10% movement
- **Structural issue:** >10% movement

## Interpretation Guidelines

### Reading the Ratios Together

Financial KPIs behave like interconnected gears:
- **AGI%** = engine torque (leverage input)
- **Labor% + SG&A%** = friction coefficients (drag)
- **Profit%** = output horsepower (result)

Optimizing one gear helps; synchronizing all creates momentum.

### Stage Transitions

Expect temporary margin compression during:
- Major system investments
- Leadership layer additions
- Strategic hiring ahead of revenue

These are investments, not inefficiencies—if planned and time-bounded.

